European inflation slides into food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the skyrocketing growth in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro zone, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, together with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to, two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “negotiate” on inflation so that it does not have to intervene in this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, beat the 12-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation has soared in the euro area as a result of soaring food and energy prices.
Forward wheat prices increased by 88 percent and soy prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup Predicts a Government Crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats rose significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup has never before experienced such a low — 13 percent — in the case of the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the parties’ secure voters – due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters – would mean a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth for the Socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the limit necessary to have any parliamentary seats: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been so high, with 41 percent of those who rated the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as next year is concerned, the majority of the population is counting on the deterioration of the situation and only a tenth expects an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government performs poorly rather than well his functions.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent does not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By comparison, only 55 percent of the population would surely participate in "a general election to be held this Sunday" and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the service of medical consultations and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of education rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average increase in the price level of the hypermarkets of the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs gold commercial triangle was maintained by 16 percent, with the difference that this year the VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also saw an average increase of 16 percent in the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs gold commercial triangle, the usual Christmas basket of the daily Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth much higher than one thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already "fired" in December last year, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do it even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Statistical Office, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the Coke with redeemable two-liter bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
All in all, Napi Auchan’s basket was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to Christmas prices last year, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during last year's Christmas in prices felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the merchant misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, it can lose a significant profit in margin that fits the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with HUF 1720 than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only a HUF 844.
No such extremes occurred this year, since the highest price now has been HUF 1630 more than last year and the cheapest also increased with HUF 1284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer items grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent in the 12-month interval.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was already quite expensive last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case scenario, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, and can impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the golden trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved foods.
On Wednesday morning, large lines were formed in all three stores in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of appliances.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygiene circumstances prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overload of the staff do not favor the control of infections - affirms the medical-head of department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then it has not been possible to perform an important surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 cases of hospital-acquired multidrug-resistant infections have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, medical director of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections caused by multidrug-resistant agents, the rest is not known.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e., methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by AS (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once over- or under-applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, transform into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly spread under inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, e.g. wound infections or septicaemia primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with a weakened body, in the elderly or in people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special in MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, nurse staff treat them in rubber gloves and mask and there are appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Inpatients are pre-screened for MRSA in their system, but infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of the formation and contagion with multidrug-resistant pathogens - says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So the majority of cases come to light when the MRSA infections visible in the patient already occur - said the medical-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological testing should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Saves money with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare workers.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What’s more, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can be experienced also - it has added Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz - that in the hospitals of less favorable economic situation it is saved with the disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for the infection.
In the opinion of Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, where adequate preventive measures are taken, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program is apparently successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital-acquired infections due to these pathogens.
Negative breathalyzer control of police commander that caused fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the commander of the police of the district XXII has been made.
It is possible to exclude the possibility that he was driving drunk or in a dazed state the since resigned commander of the police of the district XXII, who on Tuesday hit and caused the death of a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the General Prosecutor's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the expert report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary blood alcohol control that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The then head of the police station of District XXII, on Tuesday with his private vehicle when turning into the street Kossuth Lajos of District XXII hit a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(This last fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not extenuating circumstances, the driver must always give way when turning.)
The bystander lost his life after being hospitalized.
Because of what happened, the district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is in charge of the Budapest Prosecutor’s Office of Investigation.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice President Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements worth a total of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector, in Budapest on Friday.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be made from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary, and a decision on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be taken at a later stage by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovation and research project of the University of Debrecen.
The talks also covered the construction of the 4th Metro line.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will return to the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a fee for keeping the loan at the disposal of the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that little-mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buys in the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and chalets on the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while in the Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap area of Rus.
Similarly, the capital Sofia may be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf havens in Europe, making it an outstanding destination during the other two seasons as well, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria, also strive to change their life and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Also present are the Maltese and Cypriot promoters and traditionally there are many Russian customers on the beaches of the Black Sea and in the ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, in addition to the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important to them.
The second category is the buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group is the real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, since the demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these have suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in the price of real estate considerably exceeds the growth of wages.
Fodor and the Six Hundred Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the minister level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and policy makers from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for post-period efforts to reduce emissions under the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
At present, lively discussions are taking place on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach the agreement that compared to the situation in 1990, until 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member steering board, likely within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac est Profit".
The Six Percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to preserve its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 from 1990 levels, regardless of whether the “post-2012 agreement” is signed or not, and is willing to commit to even a 30 percent reduction if the world’s other major developed regions and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to meet an 8 percent decrease.
The commitment of Hungary is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect with respect to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will fulfill - notes the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since in two years we will have to sign the international agreement on long-term climate policy, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international climate partnership.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2 ° C of the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor release recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of the services of YouTube: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar’s general operations corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
Already 139 recordings from the soldiers of the air force have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defense headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true purpose of the British Army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to the conventional television spots of recruitment - it has declared to the BBC the expert in defense Gordon Mackenzie - instead, inevitably they have some political message, since in a specific form they justify the raison d'<0xC3><0xAA>tre of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example on the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with the free downloadable shooting video games, called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can directly put himself in the place of the soldiers.
