The party is not always written in red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers in the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - that next year will be less - the working days are reorganized.
Even in the EU or in North America, holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between a national holiday, a state holiday and a public holiday.
The festive days are fundamentally related to religious festivals and historical ephemerides.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is a holiday - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven holidays written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the 1848 revolution and on October 23, the day commemorating the 1956 revolution.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st the Labor Day, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day feasts Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it is often bridged when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for the long weekends like this, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labor who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly preceding or following the feast.
This legal norm is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory, however, for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work uninterrupted even during holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, since according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our parties will coincide with mid-week or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working hours than this year.
First the agenda will be modified around the work party so that then, for four successive days, workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26 will be working day, so that in return Friday, May 2 is a holiday.
The other change relates to the feast of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will have to be done instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year during the end of the year party you can rest, since from December 24th you will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six Little Deterrents to Bitter Your Colleagues' Lives
Emails that we forget to send, sound messages that we never receive, innocent lies that pass us by without us realizing it: all of them are part of our everyday "Folklore" at work.
You have to decide whether to adapt to the little annoyances or consciously avoid the confusing situations that can irritate others.
Advice.
Sorry, I forgot to let you know that you have been sought from the marketing department," says one of your colleagues.
That's why you didn't go on a date?
At best he feels it and tries to fix the issue, maybe he calls the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to give you the message (this is the least usual solution).
Most of the time the issue is resolved by apologizing.
Before proceeding to embarrassing explanations, it is worth meditating on the things with which you can embitter the lives of your colleagues and consciously strive to avoid them.
Borrow something that isn’t yours?
There is nothing more irritating than when you want to pick up a document, an office tool or your phone and you can’t find them.
Do you remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but by this morning it's gone?
Do you find your pen lost on the desk of one of your colleagues?
Don’t take anything away from your colleagues without asking them, because they will rightly be angry with you for taking their things away.
Do not take envelopes or post-it notes from the office because it can be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they sell out ahead of time.
Do you gossip about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no good solution to stop rumors that are already running.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Don’t pass on to everyone the information (conjecture) you have about the private lives of your colleagues!
Don’t abuse your colleague’s trust when they share their innermost secrets with you!
Bury in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, even if others also know the things about him.
Are you going on sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say that you are sick and your head hurts excruciatingly, you feel bad or well, you feel that that day you prefer to rest; think about what others should do your work, your unpostponable tasks, your work for term.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something may happen to you, so you must stay at home, communicate them, so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to confront your absence the next day.
Rattles, giggles, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but do you suddenly get rid of the giggles of your colleagues?
Have you inadvertently overheard a phone conversation that would have been better off not overhearing it?
Do not annoy your colleagues with your humming, singing, loud conversations (except when you do them above their head), kicking, constant blasphemies, expressing your discontents out loud.
All these can be annoying, even if they are not deepening at the moment in a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don’t blame others if you haven’t finished something on time, forgot to send an important letter or message!
Don’t allude to the chaos that eventually reigns in the office, or to the noise that your colleagues make!
You must recognize if you have made a mistake that harms others and you must repair the fault!
Ask how you can fix your fault!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Jogging and sneakers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Do not wear a comfortable jog even if your occupation allows it!
Don’t be clumsy, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing everyday, elegant and beautiful clothes when your occupation demands it!
