The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be received in the Monetary Marking through tenders.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send forty billion dollars to tender, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continued growth of the free capital shortages that banks could lend," wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report for clients.
