A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archive documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far searchable only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his heirs.
The eleven states in charge of its management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them up to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective as of yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to search “particularly on the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, owing to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or of the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the citizens deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Centre on Antisemitism at the Technische Universit<0xC3><0xA4>t Berlin in 2006.
