They will perform in Madrid on December 23.
New fears over gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia, increases the risk of it affecting the export of fuel to Western Europe by Russia.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so every brush between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit rates.
An earlier dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The last dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, monopoly gas owner Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it would charge Ukraine more, as it has pledged to pay an extra 50 percent in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine pays 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
“Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to western Europe] via Ukraine.”
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Central Asian Soviet nations.
NHS 'must test foreign workers'
The Scottish NHS needs to monitor the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The recommendation by auditor general Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was found to be linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of how many foreign staff it has.
However, his report pointed to other checks being carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor general checked the number of foreign staff hired outside the European Economic Area, following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Paisley’s Royal Alexandra Hospital, was arrested at the airport after a jeep crashed into the doors of the airport’s terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
The NHS hopes to conduct pre-employment checks on applicants to ensure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses “Disclosure Scotland” to conduct criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Great Britain.
The auditor general’s report recommends, among other measures, that boards should rely on guidance from the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
“Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review,” the report said.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of foreign NHS staff."
BMA Scotland president Dr Peter Terry said it was “very unlikely” that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is,” he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign nationals, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general cautioned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residency permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely complied with.
This includes passport checks, work permit checks and skills checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the pre-employment policy and guidance of foreigners in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “It was in my great interest that this work be carried out in the wake of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the updated pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups – including foreigners – which they planned to publish next month.
