Saudi Arabia Arrests 208 Terrorists
Saudi Arabia has arrested 208 terrorist cell militants planning an imminent attack on oil facilities, as well as attacks on religious and security forces.
State television of the world's largest oil supplier said one of the cells was planning to smuggle missiles.
Al-Qaeda sympathizers have mounted a campaign against the local monarchy, in alliance with the United States, since 2003 following the invasion of Iraq.
A cell of eight militants made up of foreign residents was planning an attack on an oil facility in the eastern province, the TV report said.
Saudi Arabia created a force of 35,000 troops to protect the facilities of Abqaiq, the world’s largest oil plant, after a failed al-Qaeda attack in 2006.
The report, citing a statement from the Saudi Interior Minister, said 18 of those arrested belonged to a cell led by a “missile launch expert” who has entered the country.
The minister said the militants had planned to smuggle eight projectiles into the country.
Another 22 of those arrested were planning assassinations of religious leaders and security forces.
The government warned religious leaders that they must be more active in stopping Saudis traveling to Iraq from joining al-Qaeda militants to fight against allied forces and to back the Shia Muslim government, which is considered a heretic by the most extreme Saudi Sunnis.
Al-Qaeda militants are targeting many religious in Saudi Arabia who have been appointed by the authorities to support the policies of the royal family, which dominates the government.
The militants — recruited by calls from Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born leader of al Qaeda, to harass the country’s pro-Western government — targeted government-associated alien residences, government buildings and energy facilities.
"This was a big effort by the security forces, for five months of work," the interior minister's spokesman told state television.
Those arrested also include a 16-person “media cell” in Medina, whose goal was to promote “takfiri thinking” — the ideology of radical Sunni Muslims that supports violence against Muslims considered infidels and apostates.
The arrest includes 32 other people accused of giving support and financial support to the militants.
Venus's climate may give an idea of Earth's future
Venus may once have been an appropriate place for life, scientists said yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft showed the planet more closely resembling an Earth twin than had previously been observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results from the European Space Agency’s Venus Express, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a snapshot of how Earth might develop catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago."
