Gordon Brown has discovered another hole to sink into; but it still emerges
As political scandals continue in England, this one is not particularly interesting.
No influences seem to have been sold, no exorbitant hotel bills in Paris, no extramarital finger sucking.
But it has been revealed that a wealthy businessman has masqueraded contributions to the British Labour government party of more than 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) for about four years using false names, and that the party did not report him.
Two months ago, when the prime minister eluded to call an election, stupidly insulting British intelligence by declaring that opinion polls did not influence his decision, the hope was that it would provide a strong and efficient government.
But instead, like Vince Calbe, the liberal democrat leads with increasing ingenuity, because the dreaded Mr. Brown has gone from being Stalin to being Mr. Bean.
The bailout of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, demonstrated regulatory weakness and poor judgment in times of crisis.
Bad proposals to change the tax code has pitted business groups, together, against the government.
The tax authority lost 25 million personal data that revealed an unimaginable administrative blip.
