Now it’s David Abrahams’ multiple donations; Peter Watt, the Labour secretary general (and former accomplice) has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is irrevocably walking toward the exit.
Governments can reach a tipping point after they find themselves unable to govern.
People don’t believe them as politicians, but they usually suspend their disbelief when a new batch takes over.
Once it is clear that the prime minister cannot improve things, that he does not have much time left, that suspension is too much: public officials begin to fail; cabinet ministers expose themselves; the press looks for bad news; and the government gets defensive and does not focus.
On the one hand, Brown’s position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot defend himself by arguing that he is new.
Although he wanted to disown Tony Blair, he was his senior lieutenant.
The Northern Rock problems and the authority registration tax are related to the decisions Brown made as chancellor of the treasury.
And even though it’s not directly involved in Blairish mishaps — or “partner cash,” the research of political party funding — voters can assume that it is.
However, Mr. Brown’s situation is not as bad as it seems.
The plates aren't as bad as the Tories want to show.
As in Mr. Bean, no one has died, nor has anyone been directly scammed.
And the remedy, though painful, is to give what Mr. Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable and brutal government.
The new political scandal of donations is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, who likens his donations to charitable giving, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be so, but the decision is not made by him.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who is buying access to those in power.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew of Mr. Abraham’s deal, and that it was not illegal, will obviously face Jon Mendlesohn, the fundraising chief who was asked about the donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is so far uninvolved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these performances, although the bulk of the payments were made after he took control of the office in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He has been quick to condemn his party for breaking the law, but is diluted in decision-making by a family matter, a commission of inquiry into the matter — led, to a large extent, by a judge and a bishop.
In this case, the morals are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, it is a police matter.
In addition, there are other things Mr. Brown must do, such as finding a permanent and independent head for the Standards in Public Life Commission, as he has not had one for six months, and he must also push for genuine reform of party funding.
This will require hard cooperative labour with the Tories, and perhaps a renunciation of the special financial situation with the unions – bitter measures for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he must face some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a good level of support in the polls; he has two years to win voters; and the only way he can move to victory is by acting with impeccable probity and solid competition.
Sharks Cards
Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural for some dorsal fins to swim excitedly around.
Today when the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their sights set on the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion can be seen.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that are more than 30 days overdue respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a 1.4 million charge in its American consumer finance business, in part due to weakness in card borrowers.
However, it’s too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a ratings agency, the third-quarter crime rate of 3.89% was nearly one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the U.S. personal bankruptcy law (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports solid payout rates, which show how much of their debt consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that issuance volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exists: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at cash flow than asset values, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to outperform the emitters.
Incentives for consumers to continue amortizing the mortgage decrease if properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of card debt climbs the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face, by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of rapid asset re-assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial officer.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a more severe future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
