The first buses carrying Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling the exiles who ran out of cash, had no visa extensions and were waiting for the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who drove them out of their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy composed of a dozen buses, the terminal was full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport.
“I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad,” says Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today from what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers, about what happened in Baghdad and it’s safe now.”
"They say that the Mahdi army stopped killing people," he says, referring to the Shiite militia of clerical militant Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to a momentary halt.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher in the Sunni Amariyah area, returned with her two children because it was impossible to renew her visa in Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him on the phone to tell him that an allied U.S. force helped drive al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of Jordan’s newcomers was the head of a Sunni and Shiite tribe that had been driven from its home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack, after it urged citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my colleagues.”
"That's why I came back today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were drawn to the growing calm in the capital as U.S. troops entrenched groups of “concerned citizens” armed and working in cooperation with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many said they had returned because of visa denials and a lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, voiced the common suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugee visas to force people back.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq," the Sunni said.
“I can’t believe in a government that supports the criminals who set my house on fire after I left.”
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, relaxing the tension.
There is a fear that a sudden surge of refugees will re-ignite sectarian tensions and start the fight.
