Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that until now had not been raised.The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that there might be lightning on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of life of Urey-Miller, the rays caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the earliest states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500°C reign, oscillating in such a way that sub-zero temperatures can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a 'diabolical' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since since the nineties there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest research results to be presented in many Nature papers, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more characteristics in common with Earth than we had previously assumed,” says ESA.
Despite the already known tempestuous winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the Earth's poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets had agglomerated water that on Earth stayed in the oceans, but on Venus was dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
